trans-unit.source: Every role has a cardinality, which provides lower and upper bounds on the number of MBeans that can appear in that role in a given relation instance. Usually, the lower and upper bounds are both 1, with exactly one MBean appearing in the role. The cardinality only limits the number of MBeans in the role per relation instance. The same MBean can appear in the same role in any number of instances of a relation type. trans-unit.source: Factory methods that produce or lookup VarHandle instances document the set of access modes that are supported, which may also include documenting restrictions based on the variable type and whether a variable is read-only. If an access mode is not supported then the corresponding access mode method will on invocation throw an UnsupportedOperationException. Factory methods should document any additional undeclared exceptions that may be thrown by access mode methods. The get access mode is supported for all VarHandle instances and the corresponding method never throws UnsupportedOperationException. If a VarHandle references a read-only variable (for example a final field) then write, atomic update, numeric atomic update, and bitwise atomic update access modes are not supported and corresponding methods throw UnsupportedOperationException. Read/write access modes (if supported), with the exception of get and set, provide atomic access for reference types and all primitive types. Unless stated otherwise in the documentation of a factory method, the access modes get and set (if supported) provide atomic access for reference types and all primitives types, with the exception of long and double on 32-bit platforms.

Few guarantees can be made regarding node creation. Because nodes are created implicitly upon access, it may not be feasible for an implementation to determine whether a child node existed in the backing store prior to access (for example, because the backing store is unreachable or cached information is out of date). Under these circumstances, implementations are neither required to generate node change events nor prohibited from doing so.
trans-unit.target: Se pueden dar pocas garantías en cuanto a la creación de nodos.Dado que los nodos se crean implícitamente en el momento del acceso,tal vez no sea factible que una implementación determine si un nodo hijo existía en el almacén de respaldo antes del acceso (por ejemplo,porque el almacén de respaldo es inalcanzable o la información almacenada en caché está desactualizada).En esas circunstancias,las implementaciones no están obligadas a generar eventos de cambio de nodo ni se les prohíbe hacerlo.
